library(tidyverse)
library(here)
library(knitr)
library(kableExtra)
library(gt)

names <- read_csv(here("Labs", "Lab 9", "StateNames_A.csv"))

Question 1

Make a summary table of the number of babies named âAllisonâ for each state and the sex of the baby. Specifically, the table should have the following qualities: - each state should be its own row - and each sex should have its own column - if there were no babies born for that combination of state & sex there should be a 0 (not an NA)

Code 
names |>
  rename(Sex = Gender) |>
  filter(Name == "Allison") |>
  select(State, Sex, Count) |>
  group_by(State, Sex) |>
  summarize(
    Count = sum(Count)
  ) |>
  pivot_wider(names_from = Sex,
              values_from = Count,
              values_fill = 0)|>
  knitr::kable(format = "html",
               col.names =
                 c("State", "Female", "Male"),
               caption = "Number of Babies Born with the Name Allison By Sex and State"
               )

Question 2

You should have seen in the table above that âAllisonâ is a name given overwhelmingly to babies assigned âfemaleâ at birth. So, create a new dataset named allison_f which contains only the babies assigned Female at birth.

Code 
allison_f <- names |>
  rename("Sex" = "Gender") |>
  filter(Name == "Allison") |>
  select(Year, Sex, State, Count)

Question 3

Make a visualization showing how the popularity of the name âAllisonâ has changed over the years. To be clear, each year should have one observationâthe total number of Allisons born that year.

Code 
allison_f |>
  group_by(Year) |>
  summarize(
    Count = sum(Count)
  ) |>
  ggplot(mapping = (aes(x = Year, y = Count))) +
  geom_line(color = "darkblue") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c("1997":"2014"), 
                     guide = guide_axis(n.dodge = 2)) +
  scale_y_continuous(n.breaks = 8) +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "", 
       title = "Number of Babies Named Allison from 1997 to 2014") +
  theme(text = element_text(family = "Optima"))

Code 
#https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/scale_continuous.html

Question 4

Fit a linear model with the year as the explanatory variable, and the number of Allisons as the response. Similar to #3, each year should have one observationâthe total number of Allisons born that year.

Code 
allison_f |>
  group_by(Year) |>
  summarize(
    Count = sum(Count)
  ) |>
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Year, y = Count)) +
  geom_point(color = "darkblue") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", fill = "lightblue", color = "aquamarine4") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c("1997":"2014"), 
                     guide = guide_axis(n.dodge = 2)) +
  scale_y_continuous(n.breaks = 8) +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Count", title = "Number of Babies Named Allison from 1997 to 2014") +
  theme(text = element_text(family = "Optima"))

Question 6

Code 
allison_f |>
  group_by(Year) |>
  summarize(
    Count = sum(Count)
  ) |>
  lm(Count ~ Year,
     data = _) |>
  broom::augment() |>
  ggplot(mapping = aes(y = .resid, x = .fitted)) +
  geom_point(color = "darkslategray4") +
  labs(x = "Fitted", y = "Residuals", 
       title = "Residuals vs. Fitted Model on Number of Babies Named Allison from 1997 to 2014") +
  theme(text = element_text(family = "Optima"))

Question 7

What do you conclude from this model? Is my name not cool anymore?

Based on the residuals vs.Â fitted model, there appears to be a curved pattern. This demonstrates that there is a nonlinear relationship between the number of babies named Allison across the years. Based on the model, it appears that the name Allison is not as popular, but it is still increasing.

Question 8

Narrow the A name dataset (downloaded previously) down to only male-assigned babies named âAllanâ, âAlanâ, or âAllenâ. Make a plot comparing the popularity of these names over time.

Code 
names |>
  rename("Sex" = "Gender") |>
  filter(Name %in% c("Allan", "Alan", "Allen"),
         Sex == "M") |>
  group_by(Name, Year) |>
  summarize(
    Count = sum(Count)
  ) |>
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Year, y = Count, color = Name)) +
    geom_line() +
    scale_y_continuous(n.breaks = 8) +
    scale_color_manual(values = c("darkslategray4", "aquamarine3", "cyan2")) +
    labs(x = "Year", y = "Count", 
         title = "Number of Babies Named Alan, Allan, or Allen from 1997 to 2014") +
  theme(text = element_text(family = "Optima"))

Question 9

In California, Allanâs spelling of his name is the least common of the three but perhaps itâs not such an unusual name for his home state of Pennsylvania. Compute the total number of babies born with each spelling of âAllanâ in the year 2000, in Pennsylvania and in California. Specifically, the table should have the following qualities: - each spelling should be its own column - each state should have its own row - a 0 (not an NA) should be used to represent locations where there were no instances of these names

Code 
names |>
  rename("Sex" = "Gender") |>
  filter(Year == 2000,
         State %in% c("CA", "PA"),
         Name %in% c("Allan", "Alan", "Allen"),
         Sex == "M"
         ) |>
  select(Name, State, Count) |>
  group_by(Name)|>
  pivot_wider(names_from = Name,
              values_from = Count)|>
  knitr::kable(format = "html",
               col.names =
                 c("State", "Alan", "Allen", "Allan"),
               caption = "Number of Male Babies Born in 2000 by Name and State"
               )
Number of Male Babies Born in 2000 by Name and State
State Alan Allen Allan
CA 579 176 131
PA 51 56 12

Question 10

Convert your total counts to overall percents. That is, what was the percent breakdown between the three spellings in CA? What about in PA?

Code 
names |>
  rename("Sex" = "Gender") |>
  filter(Year == 2000,
         State %in% c("CA", "PA"),
         Name %in% c("Allan", "Alan", "Allen"),
         Sex == "M"
         ) |>
  group_by(Name)|>
  mutate(
    Percentage = Count/sum(Count)
  ) |>
  select(Name, State, Percentage) |>
  pivot_wider(names_from = Name,
              values_from = Percentage)|>
  gt() |>
  fmt_percent(columns = 2:4, decimals = 2)
State Alan Allen Allan
CA 91.90% 75.86% 91.61%
PA 8.10% 24.14% 8.39%

Looking at the table, it appears that California has a higher percentage of male babies born in 2000 named Alan, Allen, or Allan.

Revisions

For Question 1, I had originally used quotations to rename the gender column, however, they were unnecessary. I had also used two if_else equations to replace NA values with 0. However, there is much more efficient way that is used inside of pivot_wider. In this function I can use values_fill = 0 which fills the NA values with 0.

For question 2, I removed the y-axis label so that readers donât have to tilt their head when they are looking at the graph.

For Question 7, I changed used the residual vs.Â fitted plot to prove that the name Allison isnât growing, however that interpretation is not true. The residual plot shows that the name Allison is not as popular, but it is still increasing.

For question 8, I had changed both the colors and facets to be in terms of the Name, however both are unnecessary. For my revision, I eliminated facet_wrap, so it was only distinguished by the color.

## Question 1
Make a summary table of the number of babies named âAllisonâ for each state and the sex of the baby. Specifically, the table should have the following qualities:
- each state should be its own row
- and each sex should have its own column
- if there were no babies born for that combination of state & sex there should be a 0 (not an NA)

```{r}
names |>
  rename(Sex = Gender) |>
  filter(Name == "Allison") |>
  select(State, Sex, Count) |>
  group_by(State, Sex) |>
  summarize(
    Count = sum(Count)
  ) |>
  pivot_wider(names_from = Sex,
              values_from = Count,
              values_fill = 0)|>
  knitr::kable(format = "html",
               col.names =
                 c("State", "Female", "Male"),
               caption = "Number of Babies Born with the Name Allison By Sex and State"
               )
```
